            <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4">Recently, U.S. prosecutors are reported to be preparing to indict Comey in the Eastern District of Virginia, possibly as soon as within days. The charge is likely to be making false statements to Congress during his September 2020 testimony concerning the FBI's "Crossfire Hurricane" investigation into alleged ties between the Trump campaign and Russia.</p>
            <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4">A key factor pushing this forward is a looming statute of limitations deadline, which reportedly expires next week. The case is controversial and potentially politically charged.</p>
            <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4">When a prior U.S. attorney (Erik Siebert) resisted bringing charges due to insufficient evidence, he was replaced, and Comey's critics argue the move indicates undue political influence over the Justice Department. Some internal prosecutors have reportedly expressed doubts about the strength of evidence.</p>
            <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4">If an indictment is filed and sustained, Comey would become one of the highest-ranking former U.S. officials ever criminally charged. Politically, it heightens concerns about the Justice Department's independence and whether prosecutorial decisions are being weaponized in partisan conflicts.</p>
            
